@ns20011997 it is probably a similar issue like here: https://github.com/exceljs/exceljs/issues/669 (PR: https://github.com/exceljs/exceljs/pull/722)

if I am right, this workaround should works:
```javascript
cell.style = JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(cell.style)); //very bad way to clone anythink, but works.
cell.fill = fill
```

Steps : 
- create a file
- open it with MS excel
- select cells A1 to C5 (It's an example)
- assign a style
- close the file
- open it with exceljs
- run `ws.getCell('B2').font = {...cell.font, color: {argb: 'FF3366FF'}}`
- style of A1 to C5 will be changed

### Workaround

```javascript
const cell = ws.getCell('B2')
cell.style = {
   ...cell.style,
   font: {...cell.font, color: {argb: 'FF3366FF'}}
}
```

### Idea

May be, create a method `setStyle()` on Cell class.

```javascript
setStyle(style) {
  this.style = {...this.style, ...style}
}
```
#### Use example : 

```javascript
const cell = ws.getCell('B2')
cell.style = {
   ...cell.style,
   font: {...cell.font, color: {argb: 'FF3366FF'}}
}
```

become : 

```javascript
const cell = ws.getCell('B2')
cell.setStyle({font: {...cell.font, color: {argb: 'FF3366FF'}}})
```

#### Use example : 

```javascript
const cell = ws.getCell('B2')
cell.style = {
  ...cell.style,
  fill: {
    type: 'pattern',
    pattern: 'solid',
    fgColor: {argb: 'FFD8D8D8'}
  }
}
```

become : 

```javascript
ws.getCell('B2').setStyle({
  fill: {
    type: 'pattern',
    pattern: 'solid',
    fgColor: {argb: 'FFD8D8D8'}
  }
})
```

Creating the extension method would make the code `more readable`, it won't increase boilerplate when every extension method returns the cell instance. Unsure why this was never merged, maybe it slipped through their workload. 

Even this would be cleaner, it should hide the `spread operator` from the user and implement that in the `setStyle` function. 

```javascript
const cell = ws.getCell('B2')

const updatedCell = ws.setStyle(cell, {
  fill: {
    type: 'pattern',
    pattern: 'solid',
    fgColor: {argb: 'FFD8D8D8'}
  }
})
```
